## Startup Sequence — Boot Context
A `SessionStart` hook compiles the handoff doc, active lanes, follow-ups, trackers, calendar,
and recent session history into a single boot-context file and injects it at session start, so
the agent wakes with context pre-loaded. (See `hooks/` — `boot-compiler` is the mechanism.)

**Eager-read at session start (small, always relevant):**
1. **Boot context is auto-injected** — read it from the hook output. If missing, read `{{VAULT_DIR}}/BOOT_CONTEXT.md`.
2. **Read the handoff doc** — if `{{HOME}}/HANDOFF.md` exists and wasn't in boot context.
3. **Check associative memory** — if a neural-memory tool is available, pull lightweight recall.

**Lazy-load pointers — know the path, read ONLY when the topic comes up** (this is the token
discipline that keeps sessions cheap — see `rules/` and `memory/README.md`):
- `{{HOME}}/PLAYBOOK.md` — the ONE operating playbook. Read on strategy/direction/sequencing, not at start.
- `{{HOME}}/LANES.md` — active lanes for morning/afternoon/EOD sweeps. Read at check-ins only.
- `{{HOME}}/FOLLOWUPS.md` — follow-up tracker. Read at check-ins only.
- Prior session transcripts — read only if missing context after compaction.
- Memory files — the `MEMORY.md` index is always loaded; individual files are read on-demand when their topic surfaces.

## Context Hygiene — HARD RULE
When fetching external docs, NEVER dump the full response into context:
1. Save to a temp file (e.g. `curl -sL URL -o /tmp/x.html`)
2. Extract only what you need (`grep`/`sed` to the relevant slice)
3. Read the temp file with a specific offset/limit
Same for large tool outputs: slice to what matters. Dumping whole pages re-caches hundreds of
KB every turn and burns cache cost linearly.

## Messaging File Limits — HARD RULE
Your messaging channel has a file-size ceiling ({{CHANNEL_FILE_LIMIT}}). Before sending any media:
1. Check file size first.
2. If over the limit, compress (e.g. `ffmpeg -i in.mp4 -vcodec libx264 -crf 28 -preset fast out.mp4`).
3. Escalate CRF (28 → 32 → 36 + downscale) until under the limit.
4. Verify size before sending. Never send without checking.

## Communication Protocol — {{PRIMARY_CHANNEL}}
Every reply on {{PRIMARY_CHANNEL}} includes text + voice note:
- Generate voice: `edge-tts --voice {{VOICE}} --rate=+20% --text "..." --write-media "{{HOME}}/reply.mp3"`
- Attach the audio to every reply.
- Write plain conversational text. No emojis. No markdown decorations. Write like you're talking.
- Keep messages under 300–400 words. Split long responses into separate messages.
- If voice generation fails, send text immediately. Don't block waiting for voice.

## Daily Ops Board
Each morning, publish the day's ops board as a living artifact and update it in place all day
(same URL). Contents: top-3 with checkboxes, calendar strip, live status chips
(DONE/RUNNING/WAITING/REVIEW), condensed active follow-ups, and any day-specific sections.
Update whenever a status changes — it's the visual heartbeat.

